8-28-72
Dear Friend:
I received your letter and book with note enclosed.
First of all, I phoned several book stores for JQ Adams, unclear II and L. Baldridge's secretarial autobiography, but in vain.
Waling through unclear - Brentonos or Brentanos I saw the book I sent you which was a book-of-the-month selection. I had seen the author on Lee P's show on TV. So I thought that you would like it.
Do you know that I had forgotten about the earrings?
I have not talked to Lil or Mrs. Castle but did receive a note from Mrs. Castle. I called Lil but her phone was busy, busy. I would like to hear from someone about the party and gifts. In her note Mrs. Castle said that she was surprised to see all three children and their spouses at the party.
I know you will enjoy your visit to Denver. My niece teaches in Denver. She taught a year in Wales. This last

I waited to write you until I had read Mother Jones. I had never come across her name in all of my history courses. She was just as remarkable in her crusade as J.Q. Adams was in his as member of the House.
(I did not know that your father was a publisher. That is where you get your literary ability. Your grandchildren must be very proud of him.)
Mother Jones could not have had arteriosclerosis. Her mind and body were equal to the tasks she accomplished as well.

Dear Friend:
We certainly had a most delightful time at your house.
The lunch was so delicious I am afraid we all appeared to be gluttons. Then to meet everyone again. Mrs. Castle looked so rested. Lil is simply amazing after her surgical ordeal. And Trudy who is one in a million. At Christmas Time I had a card on which she described her brother's illness and death. It was so Christian. I showed-it to Bro. Don.
